nd Austrian Prisoner-of-War Camps of World War I -- tAfterMath: Anthropological Data from Prisoner-of-War Camps -- tEthnographic Films from Prisoner-of-War Camps and the Aesthetics of Early Cinema -- tAfterword -- tAfter the Great War: National Reconfigurations of Anthropology in Late Colonial Times -- tList of Contributors -- tName Index0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWorld War I marks a well-known turning point in anthropology, and this volume is the first to examine the variety of forms it took in Europe. Distinct national traditions emerged and institutes were founded, partly due to collaborations with the military. Researchers in the cultural sciences used war zones to gain access to »informants«: prisoner-of-war and refugee camps, occupied territories, even the front lines. Anthropologists tailored their inquiries to aid the war effort, contributed to interpretations of the war as a »struggle« between »races«, and assessed the »warlike« nature of the Balkan region, whose crises were key to the outbreak of the Great War.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched - KU Select 2018: Backlist Collection  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAnthropologyxResearchzEuropey20th century. 0aEthnologyxResearchzEuropey20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspects. 4aCultural History. 4aCulture. 4aEurope. 4aEuropean History. 4aHistory of Science. 4aHistory of the 20th Century. 4aHistory. 4aScience. 4aWar. 4aWorld War I. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aCultural History.  aCulture.  aEurope.  aEuropean History.  aHistory of Science. 